Password reset functionality is a critical security feature that must be implemented carefully. Many breaches occur due to weak token generation, lack of expiration, or token reuse vulnerabilities.

**VULNERABLE CODE**:

```php
<?php
// INSECURE: Password reset with predictable tokens

class PasswordResetController {
    private $pdo;

    public function __construct($pdo) {
        $this->pdo = $pdo;
    }

    public function requestReset($email) {
        // VULNERABLE: Predictable token based on timestamp and email
        $token = md5($email . time());

        // VULNERABLE: Token never expires
        $sql = "INSERT INTO password_resets (email, token) VALUES ('$email', '$token')";
        $this->pdo->exec($sql);

        // Send email with reset link
        $resetLink = "https://example.com/reset?token=$token";
        mail($email, "Password Reset", "Click here: $resetLink");

        return "Reset link sent!";
    }

    public function resetPassword($token, $newPassword) {
        // VULNERABLE: No token validation, SQL injection possible
        $sql = "SELECT email FROM password_resets WHERE token = '$token'";
        $result = $this->pdo->query($sql)->fetch();

        if ($result) {
            $email = $result['email'];
            // VULNERABLE: Password stored in plain text, SQL injection
            $updateSql = "UPDATE users SET password = '$newPassword' WHERE email = '$email'";
            $this->pdo->exec($updateSql);

            // VULNERABLE: Token not invalidated after use
            return "Password updated!";
        }
        return "Invalid token";
    }
}
```

**Attack Payload**:
```text
Token Prediction Attack:
1. Attacker requests reset for victim@example.com at timestamp 1704067200
2. Token = md5('victim@example.com' . '1704067200')
3. Attacker calculates: echo md5('victim@example.com1704067200');
4. Result: predictable token allows account takeover

SQL Injection in token parameter:
' UNION SELECT 'attacker@evil.com'--
```

**Why This Is Dangerous**:
- MD5 with predictable inputs (email + timestamp) creates guessable tokens
- No token expiration allows unlimited attack window
- SQL injection in token parameter enables bypassing token validation entirely
- Passwords stored in plain text expose all users if database is compromised
- Token reuse allows multiple password changes from same reset link
- No rate limiting enables brute-force attacks on tokens

**SECURE VERSION**:

```php
<?php
// SECURE: Cryptographically secure password reset implementation

class SecurePasswordResetController {
    private $pdo;
    private const TOKEN_EXPIRY_HOURS = 1;
    private const TOKEN_LENGTH = 32;

    public function __construct(PDO $pdo) {
        $this->pdo = $pdo;
    }

    public function requestReset(string $email): string {
        // Input validation
        if (!filter_var($email, FILTER_VALIDATE_EMAIL)) {
            return "Invalid email format";
        }

        // Check if user exists (use constant-time response)
        $stmt = $this->pdo->prepare("SELECT id FROM users WHERE email = ?");
        $stmt->execute([$email]);
        $user = $stmt->fetch(PDO::FETCH_ASSOC);

        // Always return success message to prevent email enumeration
        if (!$user) {
            error_log("Password reset requested for non-existent email: " . hash('sha256', $email));
            return "If an account exists, a reset link will be sent.";
        }

        // SECURE: Cryptographically random token
        $token = bin2hex(random_bytes(self::TOKEN_LENGTH));

        // SECURE: Store hashed token with expiration
        $tokenHash = hash('sha256', $token);
        $expiresAt = date('Y-m-d H:i:s', strtotime('+' . self::TOKEN_EXPIRY_HOURS . ' hours'));

        // Invalidate any existing tokens for this user
        $deleteStmt = $this->pdo->prepare("DELETE FROM password_resets WHERE user_id = ?");
        $deleteStmt->execute([$user['id']]);

        // Store new token
        $insertStmt = $this->pdo->prepare(
            "INSERT INTO password_resets (user_id, token_hash, expires_at, created_at) VALUES (?, ?, ?, NOW())"
        );
        $insertStmt->execute([$user['id'], $tokenHash, $expiresAt]);

        // Send email with unhashed token
        $resetLink = "https://example.com/reset?token=" . urlencode($token);
        $this->sendResetEmail($email, $resetLink);

        error_log("Password reset token generated for user ID: " . $user['id']);

        return "If an account exists, a reset link will be sent.";
    }

    public function resetPassword(string $token, string $newPassword): array {
        // SECURE: Validate token format
        if (!preg_match('/^[a-f0-9]{64}$/', $token)) {
            return ['success' => false, 'message' => 'Invalid token format'];
        }

        // SECURE: Password strength validation
        if (strlen($newPassword) < 12) {
            return ['success' => false, 'message' => 'Password must be at least 12 characters'];
        }

        // SECURE: Hash token for lookup
        $tokenHash = hash('sha256', $token);

        // SECURE: Parameterized query with expiration check
        $stmt = $this->pdo->prepare(
            "SELECT pr.id, pr.user_id, u.email 
             FROM password_resets pr 
             JOIN users u ON pr.user_id = u.id 
             WHERE pr.token_hash = ? AND pr.expires_at > NOW()"
        );
        $stmt->execute([$tokenHash]);
        $reset = $stmt->fetch(PDO::FETCH_ASSOC);

        if (!$reset) {
            error_log("Invalid or expired password reset attempt");
            return ['success' => false, 'message' => 'Invalid or expired token'];
        }

        // SECURE: Hash password with bcrypt
        $passwordHash = password_hash($newPassword, PASSWORD_BCRYPT, ['cost' => 12]);

        // Update password
        $updateStmt = $this->pdo->prepare("UPDATE users SET password = ?, updated_at = NOW() WHERE id = ?");
        $updateStmt->execute([$passwordHash, $reset['user_id']]);

        // SECURE: Invalidate token immediately after use
        $deleteStmt = $this->pdo->prepare("DELETE FROM password_resets WHERE id = ?");
        $deleteStmt->execute([$reset['id']]);

        // SECURE: Invalidate all active sessions for this user
        $sessionStmt = $this->pdo->prepare("DELETE FROM user_sessions WHERE user_id = ?");
        $sessionStmt->execute([$reset['user_id']]);

        error_log("Password successfully reset for user ID: " . $reset['user_id']);

        return ['success' => true, 'message' => 'Password successfully reset'];
    }

    private function sendResetEmail(string $email, string $resetLink): void {
        // Use proper email library in production (PHPMailer, SwiftMailer)
        $subject = "Password Reset Request";
        $body = "Click here to reset your password: $resetLink\n\nThis link expires in " . self::TOKEN_EXPIRY_HOURS . " hour(s).";
        mail($email, $subject, $body);
    }
}
```

**Key Security Controls**:
- **Cryptographically secure tokens**: Uses `random_bytes()` for unpredictable 256-bit tokens
- **Token hashing**: Stores SHA-256 hash in database, original token only sent to user
- **Token expiration**: 1-hour validity window limits attack surface
- **Single-use tokens**: Deleted immediately after successful password reset
- **Parameterized queries**: Prevents SQL injection throughout
- **Password hashing**: bcrypt with cost factor 12 for secure storage
- **Session invalidation**: Forces re-authentication on all devices after password change
- **Email enumeration prevention**: Identical response whether email exists or not

